            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the tax refund calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tax refund calculator gives you a quick estimate of your
                2024-2025 U.S. federal income tax refund (or balance due) using
                the same core logic as major tax software, but in a simplified,
                transparent way.
              </p>
              <p>It follows four main steps:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Estimate your <strong>total income</strong> and
                  <strong>adjusted gross income (AGI)</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtract the <strong>standard deduction</strong> or your
                  <strong>itemized deductions</strong> to get
                  <strong>taxable income</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Apply the <strong>2024-2025 federal tax brackets</strong> for
                  your filing status and subtract credits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Compare your <strong>estimated total tax</strong> to your
                  <strong>federal tax withheld</strong> to show a refund or
                  amount owed.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>1. Total income and AGI</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator starts with your wages, salary, and other taxable
                income:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Total income</strong> = Wages &amp; salary + Other
                  taxable income
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Adjusted gross income (AGI)</strong> ≈ Total income −
                  Pre‑tax contributions
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Pre‑tax contributions include things like 401(k), 403(b),
                traditional IRA, and HSA contributions that reduce your taxable
                income.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Standard deduction vs. itemized deductions</h3>
              <p>For 2024-2025, the standard deduction (approximate) is:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Single:</strong> $14,600</li>
                <li><strong>Married filing jointly:</strong> $29,200</li>
                <li><strong>Married filing separately:</strong> $14,600</li>
                <li><strong>Head of household:</strong> $21,900</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator automatically uses the standard deduction for
                your filing status unless you choose to enter a higher itemized
                deduction amount.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Taxable income</strong> = max(0, AGI − Deduction)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Applying the tax brackets</h3>
              <p>
                U.S. federal income tax is progressive: different portions of
                your income are taxed at different rates. The calculator applies
                the 2024-2025 marginal tax brackets for your filing status to
                your taxable income.
              </p>
              <p>Conceptually:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Estimated tax before credits</strong> = Sum of (income
                  in each bracket × bracket rate)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Credits and Child Tax Credit estimate</h3>
              <p>
                Next, the calculator subtracts credits from your tax. It
                estimates the <strong>Child Tax Credit (CTC)</strong> based on
                the number of dependents under 17 and your income, then
                subtracts any additional non‑refundable credits you enter.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Total credits</strong> ≈ Child Tax Credit + Other
                  credits
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Tax after credits</strong> = max(0, Tax before credits
                  − Total credits)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>5. Refund vs. amount owed</h3>
              <p>
                Finally, the calculator compares your estimated total tax to the
                federal income tax already withheld from your paychecks (and
                other forms).
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Refund</strong> = max(0, Withholding − Tax after
                  credits)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Amount owed</strong> = max(0, Tax after credits −
                  Withholding)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Understanding your results</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Estimated federal refund / amount owed:</strong> The
                  main number showing whether you’re likely to get money back or
                  owe when you file.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total income:</strong> Wages plus other taxable income
                  before deductions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Taxable income:</strong> The portion of your income
                  that is actually subject to federal income tax after
                  deductions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Estimated tax:</strong> Your federal income tax
                  liability after applying brackets and credits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Effective tax rate:</strong> Estimated tax divided by
                  total income. This is usually lower than your top marginal
                  rate.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <p>
                To keep the tool fast and easy to use, we make several
                simplifying assumptions:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Only <strong>federal income tax</strong> is estimated (no
                  state or local tax).
                </li>
                <li>
                  We use approximate
                  <strong>2024-2025 brackets and standard deductions</strong>
                  based on current IRS guidance.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Child Tax Credit and other credits are simplified and may not
                  match your exact eligibility.
                </li>
                <li>
                  We do not model every schedule or form (e.g., self‑employment
                  tax, AMT, complex investment income, business losses).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For complex situations—self‑employment, rental properties, large
                capital gains, stock options, multi‑state income, etc.—you
                should use full tax software or work with a professional.
              </p>

              <h2>Tips to improve your estimate</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Use your latest <strong>pay stub</strong> to enter
                  year‑to‑date wages and federal withholding.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Have last year’s <strong>Form 1040</strong> handy to compare
                  income, deductions, and credits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you expect major changes (raise, job change, marriage, new
                  child), run the calculator again mid‑year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use the results to adjust your <strong>Form W‑4</strong> so
                  your withholding better matches your expected tax.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is my data stored or sent anywhere?</h3>
              <p>
                No. All calculations run in your browser. The numbers you enter
                are not saved to a server or associated with your identity.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for prior tax years?</h3>
              <p>
                This version is tuned for the 2024-2025 tax year. Prior years
                used different brackets, deductions, and credit rules, so the
                estimate would not be reliable for earlier returns.
              </p>

              <h3>What if I’m self‑employed?</h3>
              <p>
                You can still use the calculator by entering your
                <strong>net self‑employment income</strong> as “Other taxable
                income” and including your estimated federal tax payments in
